        <a href="#faq4" class="card-link" data-toggle="collapse">
          How long does the smell last?
        </a>
      </div>
      <div id="faq4" class="collapse" data-parent="#accordian">
        <div class="card-body">
          <p class="small text-bold text-muted">This is a hard question.</p>

          <p class="text-muted small"><span class="text-bold">First:</span> It’s very important to note that these perfumes DOES NOT last as long as the original in store would. If you are used to the original and you can spend the amounts charged for the originals please don’t buy these at this price and expect the lasting power of the ones in store.</p>

          <p class="text-muted small"><span class="text-bold">Second:</span> Every single perfume is different and cannot be expected to have the same lasting power as some scents are meant to be lighter and some heavier. For example: Dolce & Gabbana Light Blue EDT is designed to be a lighter fragrance than Tom Ford’s Black Orchid.</p>

          <p class="text-muted small"><span class="text-bold">Third:</span> Your skin & diet plays a huge roll. We have had clients who bought the same perfume but the one said it lasts up to 7-8 hours on her skin, where the other said 30 minutes. Another example is: Some people tested the ORIGINALS and it didn’t even last 20 minutes before it was completely gone. It really depends from person to person.</p>

          <p class="text-muted small"><small class="text-bold">Fourth:</small> Heat maximizes perfume. Your neck, wrists, backs of knees, and other pulse points emit more heat than other parts of your body. And that heat actually activates and maximizes your perfume. There are times during the day where perfume might smell stronger than other times because of heat.</p>
        </div>
